
@startuml

' Define the classes and their attributes and relationships

class Person {
  +personID: String
  +phone: String
  +keywords: List<String>
  +institutionCode: String
}

class Institution {
  +institutionCode: String
  +name: String
}

class Article {
  +doi: String
  +title: String
  +authors: List<Person>
  +authorPositions: List<Integer>
}

class PeerReviewedArticle extends Article {
  +citationCount: Integer
  +reviewers: List<Person>
}

class TechnicalReport extends Article {
  +publisher: String
}

class Publisher {
  +name: String
  +journals: List<Journal>
}

class Journal {
  +name: String
  +impactFactor: Double
  +publisher: Publisher
}

' Relationships

Person "1" --o"0..*" Article : worksOn
Institution "1" --o"0..*" Person : has
Publisher "1" --o"0..*" Journal : publishes
Journal "1" --o"0..*" PeerReviewedArticle : contains
Publisher "1" --o"0..*" TechnicalReport : publishes

@enduml

---

### ✅ Explanation of the Diagram:

- **`Person`**: Represents a researcher. Attributes include `personID`, `phone`, `keywords`, and `institutionCode`.
- **`Institution`**: Represents a research institution. Has an `institutionCode` and a `name`.
- **`Article`**: Base class for all articles. Contains `doi`, `title`, `authors`, and `authorPositions`.
- **`PeerReviewedArticle`**: Subclass of `Article`. Adds `citationCount` and `reviewers`.
- **`TechnicalReport`**: Subclass of `Article`. Stores the `publisher` (as a string, since it's only associated with an institution).
- **`Publisher`**: Stores the name and list of journals.
- **`Journal`**: Contains a name, impact factor, and references its publisher.
- **Relationships**:
  - A `Person` can be associated with multiple `Articles` (e.g., as author or reviewer).
  - An `Institution` can have many `Persons`.
  - A `Publisher` can publish many `Journals`.
  - A `Journal` can contain many `PeerReviewedArticles`.
  - A `Publisher` can also publish `TechnicalReports`.

